Aim
To write a program that demonstrates how an object can be passed as an argument to a function and how a function can return an object in Object-Oriented Programming.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create a class with data members.
Define a member function that accepts an object of the same class as an argument.
Define another function that creates an object and returns it.
In main(), create objects of the class.
Pass an object as an argument to a member function.
Call the function that returns an object and store the returned object.
Display the result.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Number {
    int value;

public:
    // Constructor
    Number(int v = 0) {
        value = v;
    }

    // Function to add the value of another object
    void add(Number obj) {
        value = value + obj.value;
    }

    // Function that returns an object
    Number createObject(int x) {
        Number temp(x);   // create new object
        return temp;      // return object
    }

    // Display function
    void display() {
        cout << "Value: " << value << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Number n1(10), n2(20);

    cout << "Initial Values:" << endl;
    n1.display();
    n2.display();

    // Passing object as argument
    n1.add(n2);

    cout << "\nAfter Adding n2 to n1:" << endl;
    n1.display();

    // Returning an object from function
    Number n3;
    n3 = n1.createObject(50);

    cout << "\nObject Returned from Function:" << endl;
    n3.display();

    return 0;
}

Output (Result)
Initial Values:
Value: 10
Value: 20

After Adding n2 to n1:
Value: 30

Object Returned from Function:
Value: 50

Result
Thus, the program successfully demonstrates
